[1] Germany (Thuringia): domestic goose
Date: Mon 9 Jul 2007
From: Nick Honhold <nick.honhold@gmail.com>

Re: Avian influenza (125): Germany (Thuringia), domestic goose, confirmed
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Culling of all domestic birds within a 3-km (2-mile) radius of the
remote town of Wickersdorf, where the H5N1-infected goose died, began
late Friday [6 Jul 2007], the Thuringian state health ministry said."
"The subsequent control and eradication measures are prescribed by EU
legislation."
EU legislation does not require that all domestic birds within a 3-km
radius be culled, only that this be the surveillance zone. It remains
questionable whether area-culling policies such as these are effective.
There is evidence from Turkey that they may be counterproductive,
leading to resistance by keepers who do not perceive that their birds
are at higher risk and may also delay reporting because owners fear
the consequences for their neighbours.
As an indication that such policies are not necessarily required,
Turkey had an outbreak of 230 cases over 3 months in 2006, affecting
most of the country in which something like 11 000 backyard poultry
were culled per outbreak. In 2007, they had an outbreak of 18 cases
over a period of one month in a limited area of the country in which
1700 birds were culled per outbreak.
It may be that there are particular circumstances in this case that,
based on careful on-the-ground risk assessment by veterinarians
require such widespread culling. But it is vital that we do not fall
into the situation of this becoming seen as always necessary. It is
not and is not mandated by any EU regulation.
--
Nick Honhold
Consultant veterinary epidemiologist
<nick.honhold@gmail.com>
[Dr Honhold's valid observation is appreciated; information on the
considerations leading to the decision to cull all domestic fowl
within a 3-km zone around the focus (see also item 2) will be educative.
We are also grateful to Nick for forwarding the following new
reference on H5N1 in wild birds, additional to the list included in
