[3] Germany (Thuringia): domestic goose, (Saxony): wild swans
Date: Mon 9 Jul 2007
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L09706991.htm>

German authorities culled about 1200 farm and pet birds over the
weekend [2-8 Jul 2007], after a pet goose tested positive for the
lethal strain of bird flu, a government spokesman said on Monday [9 Jul 2007].
The slaughtering programme had now been completed in an exclusion
zone around Wickersdorf in Thueringen in east Germany, a Thueringen
state government spokesman said.
A pet goose in a home for mentally handicapped people had tested
positive for the lethal H5N1 strain of bird flu and all farm and pet
birds in a 3-km (2 mi) exclusion zone were culled as a precautionary
measure over the weekend, he said. The affected goose had been able
to run around freely and contact with wild birds was suspected as
being the cause, he added. Investigations into the infection were continuing.
Thueringen had re-introduced a lock-up order for farm poultry, which
must be kept indoors in areas of high-risk contact with wild birds,
such as in farms near lakes and rivers.
The east German state government of Saxony also said 2 more wild
swans in its area had tested positive for H5N1 bird flu.
The latest cases in Saxony and Thueringen mean H5N1 bird flu has been
confirmed in a total of 43 wild birds plus the pet goose in Germany
since 24 Jun [2007], a spokeswoman for the Friedrich-Loeffler
national animal diseases institute said on Monday [9 Jul 2007].
These were the 1st German cases in 10 months. They were all reported
in east and south Germany, and bird flu has not been discovered in farm birds.
Japan said it was banning imports of day-old chicks from Germany
following the bird flu case in the pet goose.
On 5 Jul [2007], H5N1 bird flu was also confirmed in 3 wild swans in France.
Last year [2006], some 13 European Union member states had confirmed
cases of bird flu -- Germany, Austria, Denmark, Italy, Greece,
Britain, the Czech Republic, Poland, Slovakia, Slovenia, Sweden,
France, and Hungary.
Bird flu has been spreading across Southeast Asia, killing 2 people
in Viet Nam last month [June 2007], the 1st deaths there since 2005.
Globally, the H5N1 virus has killed nearly 200 people out of over 300
known cases, according to the World Health Organisation (WHO). None
of the victims were from Europe.
[The village of Wickersdorf may be located on the interactive map at
<http://www.tagzania.com/item/55379>. - CopyEd.MJ]
******
[4] Viet Nam (Ca Mau)
Date: Sun 8 Jul 2007
Source: Thanh Nien News, Reuters report [edited]
<http://www.thanhniennews.com/healthy/?catid=8&newsid=29770>

A group of H5N1-infected ducks has brought the bird flu back to Viet
Nam's Southern-most province of Ca Mau, said the Animal Health
Department Saturday [7 Jul 2007].
The outbreak in Dam Doi District's Tan Trung commune wiped Ca Mau's
name off the list of bird flu-free provinces.
Currently, there are 9 other northern provinces plagued by the avian
virus: Nghe An, Hai Phong, Bac Giang, Ninh Binh, Vinh Phuc, Quang
Nam, Thai Binh, Ha Tinh, and Quang Ninh.
Last week [2-8 Jul 2007], the Veterinary Department announced that
1130 chickens and ducks had contracted the flu in Thai Binh and Nghe
An provinces.
Since the beginning of the year, 153.5 million fowls have undergone a
mass national vaccination throughout the country.
[Byline: Luu Thi Hong]
